B26</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Nahee</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Kang</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE015891%2F1"><gtr:id>1CAB2078-1E3A-4B78-97FD-B6B12DCBE947</gtr:id><gtr:title>Corporate Governance and Corporate Social Responsibility: A Varieties of Capitalism Perspective</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E015891/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The objective of the postdoctoral fellowship project is to explore corporate governance and corporate social responsibility (CSR) practices. In particular, the project addresses two questions:&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>to what extent can the different ways in which CSR is practised and corporations regulated in national economies be traced back to the different and wider institutional arrangements in their corporate governance?; and&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>what implications does the adoption of Anglo-American corporate governance have on state and non-state regulation of the corporate sector?&lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>The significance of the project is that it explores the link between two different, yet closely related, literatures, ie corporate governance and CSR. The method to be employed is qualitative, drawing from the researcher?s existing PhD data, which includes a wide range of publicly available materials (eg statistics from the OECD and the World Bank, documents published by government ministries, business associations, company reports, etc) as well as undertaking a limited amount of additional archival research and follow-up/new interviews.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-11-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-11-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>68700</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>25A7B78E-7ADB-415F-9C89-EA8CDAD964A9</gtr:id><gtr:title>Globalisation and Institutional Change in the State-Led Model: The Case of Corporate Governance in South Korea</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>New Political Economy</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/e42894b699e1e6f8b987e1e872c08a0d"><gtr:id>e42894b699e1e6f8b987e1e872c08a0d</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Kang N</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cf9bf9bc89fbfb</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>4B3F0F1A-1AA